      },
      {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "Here are the results for the paper **\"Formality is Favored: Unraveling the Learning Preferences of Large Language Models on Data with Conflicting Knowledge\"**:\n\n## Paper Overview\n\n"
      },
      {
        "citations": [],
        "type": "text",
        "text": "This paper is authored by Jiahuan Li, Yiqing Cao, Shujian Huang, and Jiajun Chen"
      },
      {
        "type": "text",
        "text": ", "
      },
      {
        "citations": [],
        "type": "text",
        "text": "from the National Key Laboratory for Novel Software Technology, Nanjing University, China"
      },
      {
        "type": "text",
        "text": ".\n\n"
      },
      {
        "citations": [],
        "type": "text",
        "text": "It was published in the Proceedings of the 2024 Conference on Empirical Methods in Natural Language Processing (EMNLP), pages 5307–5320, in Miami, Florida, USA"
      },
      {
        "type": "text",
        "text": ".\n\n"
      },
      {
        "citations": [],
        "type": "text",
        "text": "Notably, this paper was recognized among the Best Papers at EMNLP 2024"
      },
      {
        "type": "text",
        "text": ".\n\n## Key Findings\n\n"
      },
      {
        "citations": [],
        "type": "text",
        "text": "The study systematically analyzes LLMs' learning preferences for data with conflicting knowledge, finding that pretrained LLMs establish learning preferences similar to humans — i.e., preferences towards formal texts and texts with fewer spelling errors, resulting in faster learning and more favorable treatment of knowledge in data with such features when facing conflicts."
      },
      {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "\n\n"
      },
      {
        "citations": [],
        "type": "text",
        "text": "This finding is generalizable across models and languages and is more evident in larger models."
      },
      {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "\n\n"
      },
      {
        "citations": [],
        "type": "text",
        "text": "An in-depth analysis reveals that LLMs tend to trust data with features that signify consistency with the majority of data, and it is possible to instill new preferences and erase old ones by manipulating the degree of consistency with the majority data."
      },
      {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "\n\n## Motivation\n\n"
      },
      {
        "citations": [],
        "type": "text",
        "text": "While large language models have shown excellent performance on many knowledge-intensive tasks thanks to massive pretraining data, pretraining data tends to contain misleading and even conflicting information, and it is intriguing to understand how LLMs handle these noisy data during training."
      },
      {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "\n\n## Resources\n\n- **ACL Anthology**: https://aclanthology.org/2024.emnlp-main.304/\n- **arXiv**: https://arxiv.org/abs/2410.04784\n- **DOI**: 10.18653/v1/2024.emnlp-main.304"
      }
    ],
